{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-7","id":"msg_01HhFKiDHiSJwdPGKKCXJeMo","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Looking at this problem, I need to evaluate $I = \\int_0^\\infty t^{-1/2} e^{-1985(t + 1/t)}\\,dt$.\n\n**Step 1: Substitution $t = u^2$**\n\nThen $dt = 2u\\,du$, $t^{-1/2} = 1/u$, and $t + 1/t = u^2 + 1/u^2$:\n$$I = \\int_0^\\infty \\frac{1}{u} e^{-1985(u^2 + 1/u^2)} \\cdot 2u\\,du = 2\\int_0^\\infty e^{-1985(u^2 + 1/u^2)}\\,du$$\n\n**Step 2: Let $a = 1985$, $J = \\int_0^\\infty e^{-a(u^2 + 1/u^2)}\\,du$**\n\nApply substitution $u \\to 1/u$ (i.e., $v = 1/u$, $du = -dv/v^2$):\n$$J = \\int_0^\\infty \\frac{1}{v^2} e^{-a(v^2 + 1/v^2)}\\,dv$$\n\n**Step 3: Average the two expressions for $J$:**\n$$2J = \\int_0^\\infty \\left(1 + \\frac{1}{u^2}\\right) e^{-a(u^2 + 1/u^2)}\\,du$$\n\n**Step 4: Substitute $w = u - 1/u$**\n\nThen $dw = (1 + 1/u^2)\\,du$, and $w^2 = u^2 - 2 + 1/u^2$, so $u^2 + 1/u^2 = w^2 + 2$. As $u: 0 \\to \\infty$, $w: -\\infty \\to \\infty$:\n$$2J = \\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty e^{-a(w^2 + 2)}\\,dw = e^{-2a} \\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty e^{-aw^2}\\,dw$$\n\n**Step 5: Use the given Gaussian**\n\nWith $\\int_{-\\infty}^\\infty e^{-aw^2}\\,dw = \\sqrt{\\pi/a}$:\n$$2J = e^{-2a}\\sqrt{\\pi/a}$$\n\nSo $I = 2J = e^{-2a}\\sqrt{\\pi/a}$ with $a = 1985$:\n$$I = \\sqrt{\\frac{\\pi}{1985}}\\, e^{-3970}$$\n\nANSWER: $\\sqrt{\\pi/1985}\\,e^{-3970}$\nCONFIDENCE: high"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":506,"cache_read_input_tokens":19541,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":506},"output_tokens":62,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"75901baf-adc0-4916-9967-7f2daa4da8ba","uuid":"16e4c48d-6f47-4f90-9de5-572869e7a60f","request_id":"req_011CbDQRfac8aTKbRfsPJKFm"}
